## 4. Global quality control with NanoPlot

NanoPlot is used to evaluate read length distribution, mean read quality, N50, and other sequencing metrics. This step can be applied to raw reads, Dorado-trimmed reads, primer-trimmed reads, or filtered reads.

### NanoPlot for all raw reads combined

```bash
#!/bin/bash
set -euo pipefail

OUTDIR="NanoPlot_All"
mkdir -p "$OUTDIR"

# Find all FASTQ.gz files inside barcodeXX folders.
FASTQS=$(find . -maxdepth 2 -type f -path "./barcode*/*.fastq.gz")

echo "📊 Generating NanoPlot for ALL raw reads..."

NanoPlot \
  --fastq $FASTQS \
  -o "$OUTDIR" \
  --threads 16 \
  --loglength \
  --N50 \
  --plots hex dot kde \
  --title "NanoPlot - All Barcodes Combined"

echo "✅ NanoPlot finished. Report: $OUTDIR/NanoPlot-report.html"
```

### What this allows you to inspect

- Read length distribution.
- Mean read quality.
- N50.
- Presence of reads that are too short or too long.
- Whether the expected 16S amplicon size range is represented.

