## 5. Length and quality filtering with NanoFilt

NanoFilt can filter reads according to quality and length. For long 16S amplicons, it may be useful to retain reads within a range compatible with the expected amplicon size.

Two filtering options are shown below.

---

### 5.1. Strict filtering: Q10 and 1300–1700 bp

This filtering strategy retains reads with:

- Minimum length: 1300 bp.
- Maximum length: 1700 bp.
- Minimum quality: Q10.

```bash
#!/bin/bash
set -euo pipefail

OUTDIR="NanoFilt_Q10_1300-1700"
mkdir -p "$OUTDIR"

for bc in barcode*; do
  echo "📌 Filtering $bc ..."

  if compgen -G "$bc/*.fastq.gz" > /dev/null; then
    zcat "$bc"/*.fastq.gz | \
      NanoFilt -l 1300 --maxlength 1700 -q 10 | \
      gzip > "$OUTDIR/${bc}_1300-1700bp_Q10.fastq.gz"

    echo "✅ Saved: $OUTDIR/${bc}_1300-1700bp_Q10.fastq.gz"
  else
    echo "⚠️ No FASTQ.gz files found inside $bc. Skipping."
  fi
done

echo "✅ Filtering finished for all barcodes."
```

### When to use this criterion

This criterion is useful if the expected amplicon is close to full-length 16S and you want to retain a relatively narrow read-length range.

